Cheese is literally just milk without the whey, removing the high tryptophan portion from it. Milk is already basically the best food and cheese somehow even a step above that. There are thousands of amazing varieties to try in a lifetime. Have you heard of Reblochon or Dontroon?

The best thing to do as a Dr. Ray Peat follower is to just get really into cheese. Join an internet forum about cheese discussion (even the cheese subreddit), research less known varieties, befriend a cheesemonger, just acquire a taste and appreciation for cheeses and enjoy them.

Everyone knows about balancing muscle meats with gelatin (broths, etc.), but the different cuts of meat themselves have different type of protein. E.g. tougher cuts of meat like brisket are more gelatinous and have less tryptophan. The tougher cuts of meat you do eat, the better.

"Shank, round, flank, plate, chuck, and brisket" are listed as the toughest ones, but I am pretty sure there are some esoteric cuts that butchers only know about... Zero HP Lovecraft knows about this stuff well he redpilled me on less known meat cuts a few years ago... Ask him...
